On August 7, 2020, the United States celebrated the 238th anniversary of the establishment of the Purple Heart, originally known as the Badge of Military Merit. The Purple Heart is a medal awarded to military service members who have been wounded or killed in action. It was created by General George Washington during the nation's war for independence. The medal bears Washington's profile and symbolizes the courage, valor, and devotion shown by all recipients. The article emphasizes the gratitude and admiration for the heroes of America's Armed Forces and the sacrifices they make to protect the nation's peace and prosperity. The First Lady and President also pay tribute to Purple Heart recipients, their families, and Gold Star Families, and express their commitment to honoring the legacy of service for generations to come.